Lab Tasks
Task 1: Setting Up the Environment and Creating Line Plots
Subtask 1.1: Import Required Libraries
First, let's import the necessary libraries and set up our working environment.

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

# Set up the plotting style
plt.style.use('default')
print("Matplotlib version:", plt.__version__)
Subtask 1.2: Create Your First Line Plot
Let's create a simple line plot to visualize temperature changes over a week.

# Sample data: Daily temperatures for a week
days = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']
temperatures = [22, 25, 23, 27, 29, 31, 28]

# Create a line plot
plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
plt.plot(days, temperatures, marker='o', linewidth=2, markersize=8)

# Add labels and title
plt.title('Daily Temperature Throughout the Week', fontsize=16, fontweight='bold')
plt.xlabel('Days of the Week', fontsize=12)
plt.ylabel('Temperature (°C)', fontsize=12)

# Rotate x-axis labels for better readability
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# Add grid for better readability
plt.grid(True, alpha=0.3)

# Adjust layout to prevent label cutoff
plt.tight_layout()

# Display the plot
plt.show()
Subtask 1.3: Create Multiple Line Plots
Now let's create a more complex line plot with multiple data series.

# Sample data: Temperature comparison between two cities
days_numeric = list(range(1, 8))
city_a_temps = [22, 25, 23, 27, 29, 31, 28]
